In a #small pot{}, combine @white rice{3/4%cup}, @water{1 1/4%cups}, and a pinch of
@salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until
rice is tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, wash and dry produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @yellow onion{1}; finely
chop a few slices until you have 2 TBSP (4 TBSP for 4 servings). Zest and quarter
@lime{1}. Dice @tomato{1} into 1/4-inch pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{a drizzle} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add
sliced onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned, ~{3-5%minutes}.

While onion cooks, in a #small bowl{}, combine @smoky red pepper crema{2%tbsp},
@sour cream{1.5%tbsp}, and a squeeze of lime juice. In a separate small bowl,
combine @Tex-Mex paste{1}, @beef stock concentrate{1}, chopped onion, tomato, and
a squeeze of lime juice; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Pat @diced steak{8%oz} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with salt and
pepper. Once onion has cooked, add steak to pan and cook, stirring occasionally,
until browned, about ~{3%minutes}. Stir in Tex-Mex paste and stock concentrate.
Cook, stirring, until steak is coated and cooked to desired doneness, ~{1-2%minutes}
more. Remove from heat and stir in a squeeze of lime juice.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in a pinch of lime zest. Divide rice between bowls;
top with Tex-Mex steak and drizzle with red pepper-lime crema. Top with pico de
gallo and serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.